    teachingBody:
      "Some men, after a lapse, perform a grand collapse — the dramatic remorse, the sweeping vow, the inner courtroom, the long stretch of self-punishment. They mistake the drama for the seriousness of the practice. It is the opposite. The drama is wasted energy that the next lapse will use.\n\nThe Pilgrim's return is clean. Stand up. Name what happened, briefly and honestly. Notice the lesson. Repair what can be repaired. Take the next clean step. No theater, no grand vow, no public penance. Just the return.\n\nThis is harder than the drama. The drama feels like seriousness. The clean return feels like nothing. But the clean return is what actually preserves the practice. The drama burns the energy the practice needs.",
