      "Cleaning a wound is not denying the wound. It is honoring it through the work of healing. The opposite of cleaning a wound is not ignoring it. It is worshiping it: returning to it, picking at it, telling its story repeatedly, organizing one's interior around it.\n\nThe practice eventually requires this distinction. The shadow has been seen; the patterns have been named. Now they must be treated rather than enshrined. Treatment is concrete: changes in behavior, changes in environment, changes in relational structure, sometimes professional help, sometimes specific small daily practices. Enshrinement is talking and re-talking the wound without changing anything.\n\nThe Healer's discipline is to move from naming to treating. The naming was the first work. The treating is the next. The man who does both heals; the man who only names stays at the entrance.",
