      "The day before the crown is not a different day. It is the same practice, performed once more, with the same attention. There is a temptation to treat it as ceremonial — to relax slightly, knowing the milestone is essentially achieved. This temptation is the compulsion's last good argument. Refuse it.\n\nThe crown is not received on day ninety because day ninety is special. It is received on day ninety because the man has performed the practice for eighty-nine days, including today, with attention. The crown is the cumulative integrity of the days. Today is one of those days. Treat it as one.\n\nThe Guardian holds the gate on day eighty-nine as if there were many more days to come. Because there are. The crown opens the Long Path, where the practice continues in a different rhythm but the same essential form. The discipline of today is rehearsal for what comes after.",
